"I think your fear is too great," returned Mrs. Hobart. "Go on in your usual way;
                  keep your mind calm; be as careful in regard to diet, and you need fear no
                  danger."

"Yes. And I must accept it, notwithstanding I have no angry feelings against him;
                  and, but for the hasty step he has now taken, would have most willingly asked his
                  pardon."

"I have been very ill, lately," Alfred Graham replied, in a mournful tone;
                     former thoughts and feelings rushing back upon him in consequence of this
                     unexpected interview, and quite subduing him.

"Any such foolish and rash resolution on your part, I should regret very much;
                  for, unkindly and unfeelingly as you have acted towards me, I have no wish to
                  dissolve the tie of nature."
